{"type":"message","id":"33902640","parentId":"8ad399fd","timestamp":"2026-03-22T02:18:36.572Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Zach is being sweet and apologetic. He got confused about the GPU specs and is worried he \"squashed\" my model choice. But actually, the RTX 5000 with 16GB VRAM and 30GB system RAM should still work for Qwen3.5-35B Q4_K_M. The model will use memory-mapped storage for weights that don't fit in VRAM, which vLLM handles.\n\nBut wait — the A4000 has 45GB RAM (not VRAM, system RAM). That's actually more system RAM which helps with memory-mapped models. Let me think again...\n\nActually no — RTX 5000 still has better compute and memory bandwidth. \n\nThe key specs that matter for inference are compute (RTX 5000 wins with 48 Tensor-TFLOPS vs RTX 4000's 32), memory bandwidth (RTX 5000's 768 GB/s vs RTX 4000's 448 GB/s), and VRAM (both have 16GB). The A4000 with 45GB system RAM might handle memory-mapped overflow better, but vLLM's CPU offloading isn't as efficient as GPU compute, so the RTX 5000's superior bandwidth and compute still make it the better choice despite the A4000's larger system RAM. The RTX 5000 is the right pick—I'll tell Zach to go ahead and spin it up.","thinkingSignature":"413da21876e5f96f4d03c975b0fe633e7054217dbd7e52e46c85d4e409ab75ef"},{"type":"text","text":"Haha no don't worry — RTX 5000 still stands. Better compute and memory bandwidth than the A4000 anyway, and the 16GB VRAM ceiling is the same across all of them. The RAM difference (30GB vs 45GB) only matters for CPU offloading which isn't the bottleneck here — GPU compute and bandwidth are.\n\nGo RTX 5000, model stays as Qwen3.5-35B-Q4_K_M. Let's spin it up."}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":43,"output":390,"cacheRead":18272,"cacheWrite":288,"totalTokens":18993,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":17741459