{"type":"message","id":"c928eb5e","parentId":"2ed85c1d","timestamp":"2026-03-22T02:21:10.606Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Zach is setting up a Paperspace Gradient notebook. He's asking about:\n1. Template: PyTorch vs Hugging Face Transformers vs something else\n2. Whether to use a container image in advanced options\n\nFor running vLLM with Qwen models, the best approach would be:\n- PyTorch template is fine as a base\n- Or better, use a vLLM container image directly if Paperspace supports custom images\n- Could also use the \"Custom\" container option with a vLLM base image\n\nFor Paperspace Gradient specifically:\n- They have PyTorch templates available\n- For vLLM, you typically want a PyTorch base with vLLM installed\n\n\n- Paperspace likely has a PyTorch template as the standard starting point, and from there we can install vLLM on top\n- Alternatively, if they offer a \"Custom\" container option, we could use `vllm/vllm-openai:latest` as the base image, which already has vLLM configured with the OpenAI API server that's compatible with OpenClaw\n- The PyTorch template is the most straightforward path—Paperspace's Gradient platform is built around it and will have the necessary GPU support baked in\n\n, so we just need to install vLLM on top","thinkingSignature":"040b304871c9ee798dbc6d067086ca21d349223f1a7f801643b7cbbb027ce048"},{"type":"text","text":"PyTorch template — Paperspace has GPU support baked in, and we just need vLLM on top. Skip the Hugging Face template, it's heavier than we need.\n\nFor the container image — if there's a \"Custom\" option, use `vllm/vllm-openai:latest`. That's the vLLM server with the OpenAI-compatible API already configured, which is exactly what OpenClaw would call. If Paperspace doesn't expose custom containers at that level, PyTorch + `pip install vllm` works fine too."}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":0,"output":374,"c