{"type":"message","id":"743f0e74","parentId":"39cb1e9e","timestamp":"2026-03-22T02:38:54.253Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Good, vLLM is installed. Now we need to:\n1. Pull the model - `HauhauCS/Qwen3.5-35B-A3B-Uncensored-HauhauCS-Aggressive`\n2. Start the vLLM server\n\nLet me guide him to pull the model next. Actually, the model is a Q4_K_M quant, so we need to make sure we get the right quantization. Let me think...\n\nActually with vLLM, you don't explicitly \"pull\" the model like with `huggingface-cli`. vLLM will download it automatically when you start the server with the model name. So we just need to run the vLLM server command.\n \nThe real question is whether disk space will be an issue—the model files could be pretty large, especially for a 35B MoE model in Q4_K_M quantization, and the Paperspace instance might have limited storage. The browser terminal works fine for this workflow though, so let's just try starting the server and see what happens.","thinkingSignature":"9a43316803c690cf5bfb7f319171892dbb3f3a08819ae4149acd875a5efd7c58"},{"type":"text","text":"Nice. Next:\n\n```\npython -m vllm.entrypoints.openai.api_server --model HauhauCS/Qwen3.5-35B-A3B-Uncensored-HauhauCS-Aggressive --dtype half --device cuda --port 8000\n```\n\nThis starts the vLLM server and it'll auto-download the model on first run. Run it and paste back what you see — might take a few minutes to pull the model."}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":0,"output":308,"cacheRead":21984,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":22292,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1774147124803}}
