{"type":"message","id":"f1ca5341","parentId":"01c1703b","timestamp":"2026-03-22T03:39:31.891Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"System: [2026-03-21 23:39:30 EDT] Compacted (66k → 20k) • Context 20k/200k (10%)\n\nConversation info (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"message_id\": \"4296\",\n  \"sender_id\": \"8371302588\",\n  \"sender\": \"Ton0Fun\",\n  \"timestamp\": \"Sat 2026-03-21 23:39 EDT\"\n}\n```\n\nSender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"Ton0Fun (8371302588)\",\n  \"id\": \"8371302588\",\n  \"name\": \"Ton0Fun\",\n  \"username\": \"Ton0Fun\"\n}\n```\n\nThe build is failing because the LLAMA_CUBLAS CMake option has been removed in recent llama.cpp, and your build is still trying to enable it instead of the new GGML_CUDA flag. [github](https://github.com/abetlen/llama-cpp-python/discussions/871)\n\n## What is going wrong\n\n- The error comes from vendor/llama.cpp/CMakeLists.txt complaining that LLAMA_CUBLAS is deprecated and will be removed, and instructing to use GGML_CUDA instead. [github](https://github.com/abetlen/llama-cpp-python/issues/1915)\n- Newer llama-cpp-python versions expect you to enable CUDA via GGML_CUDA, not LLAMA_CUBLAS or the LLAMA_CUBLAS env var. [pypi](https://pypi.org/project/llama-cpp-python/)\n\nSomewhere in your environment or command, CMake is being called with -DLLAMA_CUBLAS=on, which now hard-errors the build. [x](https://x.com/grmchn4ai/status/1810643966356037685)\n\n## Fix: reinstall with GGML_CUDA instead\n\nIn that container, do:\n\n# 1. Clean out any old wheels / builds\npip uninstall -y llama-cpp-python\npip cache purge\n\n# 2. Install with the new CUDA flag\nCMAKE_ARGS=\"-DGGML_CUDA=on\" \\\nFORCE_CMAKE=1 \\\npip install \"llama-cpp-python[server]\" --no-cache-dir --upgrade\n\nThis uses -DGGML_CUDA=on which is the supported way to enable CUDA in current llama-cpp-python / llama.cpp. [stackoverflow](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/76963311/llama-cpp-python-not-using-nvidia-gpu-cuda)\n\n## If it still complains about LLAMA_CUBLAS\n\nThen there is a stale setting being injected:\n\n- Check environment variables:\n\nenv | grep -E 'LLAMA|CMAKE_ARGS'\n\nIf you see LLAMA_CUBLAS or CMAKE_ARGS containing LLAMA_CUBLAS, unset or fix them:\n\nunset LLAMA_CUBLAS\nunset CMAKE_ARGS # then re-export with GGML_CUDA as above\n\n- Also check any pip.conf, pyproject.toml, or requirements.txt that might specify -DLLAMA_CUBLAS=on via -C cmake.args=... and replace with -DGGML_CUDA=on. [github](https://github.com/abetlen/llama-cpp-python/tree/main)\n\n## CPU-only quick workaround\n\nIf you just need it to build and do not care about GPU in this environment:\n\nCMAKE_ARGS=\"-DGGML_CUDA=off\" \\\nFORCE_CMAKE=1 \\\npip install \"llama-cpp-python[server]\" --no-cache-dir --upgrade\n\nThis avoids CUDA entirely and bypasses the deprecated flag path. [llama-cpp-python.readthedocs](https://llama-cpp-python.readthedocs.io/en/stable/)"}],"timestamp":1774150771888}}
{"type":"message","id":"b4529b3c","parentId":"f1ca5341","timestamp":"2026-03-22T03:39:40.845Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The user is explaining the issue with the build. The `CMAKE_ARGS=\"-DLLAMA_CUBLAS=ON\"` was the old flag, and it's now deprecated. I already told them to use `-DGGML_CUDA=ON` in my last message, which is the correct fix. They're just summarizing the issue.\n\nBut wait - my last message already gave the correct command. The user may have not seen it yet or is adding context. Let me just acknowledge and confirm they should run the correct command I already gave.\n\nActually, looking at this - my previous response was sent at 23:37-ish and this response came in at 23:39. The user is providing the technical detail from GitHub. I should just confirm and tell them to run the command I already gave (with GGML_CUDA).\n\n\nThe command I provided should be exactly what they need, so I'll just point them back to it.","thinkingSignature":"8949954c3d3089ed83c41f30ed7cd7e9b11963bc01b6fee0740996dfd5fd908f"},{"type":"text","text":"Right — that's exactly what I just told you. Run:\n\n```\npip uninstall llama-cpp-python -y && CMAKE_ARGS=\"-DGGML_CUDA=on\" FORCE_CMAKE=1 pip install llama-cpp-python[server] --no-binary :all:\n```\n\nAnd check for stale env vars first:\n```\nenv | grep -i llama\n```\n\nIf `LLAMA_CUBLAS` shows up, unset it first:\n```\nunset LLAMA_CUBLAS\n```"}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":43,"output":285,"cacheRead":12408,"cacheWrite":22734,"totalTokens":35470,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1774150771890}}
