{"type":"message","id":"6e003446","parentId":"283c8cc7","timestamp":"2026-03-22T03:44:42.610Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"I don't see bot commands stored in the config. OpenClaw sets them through BotFather's API automatically. Let me check if there's a way to manage commands via OpenClaw or if there's a Telegram API call I can make.\n\nActually, Telegram bot commands are managed through the BotFather bot API. OpenClaw likely calls the Telegram Bot API to set commands when it configures the bot. \n\nLooking at the Telegram config, the bot token is `8587631426:AAHvqmo--g25LqsClCWCXj4m617cn2v7V7Q`. I can use the Telegram Bot API to delete commands. The API endpoint would be:\n\n\n`https://api.telegram.org/bot<token>/deleteMyCommands`\n\nI should verify this approach works — the BotFather `/setcommands` interface and the API both manage the same command list, so calling `deleteMyCommands` should clear them. But I'm also noticing Zach mentioned Claw set these commands, so I should check if OpenClaw has a built-in way to manage them rather than making direct API calls.\n\nActually, I realize I can make HTTP requests directly without needing a tool — `exec` can handle curl calls. The cleanest approach would be to first retrieve the current commands with `getMyCommands`, then selectively delete the ones I want to remove using `deleteMyCommands`.\n\nBut wait, `deleteMyCommands` removes everything at once. If I want to be selective, I'd need to use `setMyCommands` to replace the entire list with just the commands I want to keep. So I should probably ask Zach which specific commands he wants to remove, or have him share the full list so I can help him figure out what to delete.\n\nActually, I just realized I can call the Telegram Bot API directly using curl through exec. Let me retrieve the current command list first to see what we're working with.","thinkingSignature":"f6b3bdd88e2acac6d172192a3de33356ac648e97d79fc8edc8e023fec1aec2ed"},{"type":"text","text":"OpenClaw doesn't have a built-in command for this — but I can call the Telegram Bot API directly. Let me see what commands are currently set:\n\n```\ncurl -s \"https://api.telegram.org/bot8587631426:AAHvqmo--g25LqsClCWCXj4m617cn2v7V7Q/getMyCommands\"\n```\n\nPaste the result here."}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":27546,"output":477,"cacheRead":12408,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":40431,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1774151059864}}
