{"type":"message","id":"b5f5abd2","parentId":"e013a5ca","timestamp":"2026-03-22T03:55:27.631Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The Paperspace Gradient notebook URL isn't accessible from the public internet. That's expected — it's behind Paperspace's network.\n\nOK let me think about this differently. I need to execute commands on the Paperspace notebook. The ways I could do this:\n\n1. Jupyter REST API (terminals, kernels) - but the URL isn't accessible from outside Paperspace's network\n2. Paperspace Jobs API - would let me run commands on the machine, but the API endpoints don't seem to be working as expected\n3. SSH - but we don't have the notebook's SSH details\n\nActually wait — the notebook IS accessible via SSH for Paperspace Gradient, but the hostname needs to be resolved within Paperspace's network. \n\nI could potentially use the Paperspace API to retrieve the notebook's SSH connection details, or maybe I should try a different approach entirely like building llama.cpp from source. Let me focus on getting the Paperspace Jobs API working first since that's the most direct way to execute commands on the notebook.\n\nLooking at the API response more carefully, I notice the project handles and recent activity data. The workload ID `r0p341v4x26re7h` from the Qwen 3.5 notebook might be what I need to query the jobs endpoint directly. Let me try constructing the right API call to get the notebook's actual connection details and state.","thinkingSignature":"e7303ce79df7da7709d68a4e535802f92ff107b33919dadce14a9821068af1da"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_fv2gspvzy53s_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"curl -s -X GET \"https://api.paperspace.io/projectJobs?projectId=711645\" -H \"x-api-key: 5f1a3ab0e0a54c134559cad7482f51\" 2>&1 | head -100","timeout":15}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":49145,"output":369,"cacheRead":12408,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":61922,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774151716755}}
{"type":"message","id":"9561020a","parentId":"b5f5abd2","timestamp":"2026-03-22T03:55:28.938Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_fv2gspvzy53s_1","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"{\"error\":{\"name\":\"Error\",\"status\":404,\"message\":\"There is no method to handle GET /projectJobs?projectId=711645\",\"statusCode\":404}}"}],"details":{"status":"completed","exitCode":0,"durationMs":1300,"aggregated":"{\"error\":{\"name\":\"Error\",\"status\":404,\"message\":\"There is no method to handle GET /projectJobs?projectId=711645\",\"statusCode\":404}}","cwd":"C:\\Users\\Zwmar\\.openclaw\\workspace"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1774151728936}}
{"type":"message","id":"96111986","parentId":"9561020a","timestamp":"2026-03-22T03:55:35.004Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Let me try a different approach. Let me see what the Paperspace Python SDK has access to. The gradient package that I installed is the DigitalOcean version, not Paperspace. Let me check if there's a separate Paperspace SDK.Actually, let me look at the OpenClaw docs for Paperspace/node management to see how it integrates with Paperspace.Actually, let me try something else. Let me check if OpenClaw itself has any Paperspace integration or if there's a node agent that can be installed on Paperspace.\n\nActually, you know what, let me take a completely different approach. Let me use the `openclaw node` command to set up the Paperspace notebook as an OpenClaw node. If OpenClaw can talk to nodes, then I could potentially use the node to execute commands.","thinkingSignature":"0ab4d8138b7cab95fd82acac5198c60fb1f85c9a7b7dd31b29e2b3e288657fc7"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_aj2bo5k5hjm8_1","name":"read","arguments":{"path":"C:\\Users\\Zwmar\\AppData\\Roaming\\npm\\node_modules\\openclaw\\docs\\cli\\node.md"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":49564,"output":214,"cacheRead":12408,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":62186,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774151728941}}
{"type":"message","id":"becacf3b","parentId":"96111986","timestamp":"2026-03-22T03:55:35.018Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_aj2bo5k5hjm8_1","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"---\nsummary: \"CLI reference for `openclaw node` (headless node host)\"\nread_when:\n  - Running the headless node host\n  - Pairing a non-macOS node for system.run\ntitle: \"node\"\n---\n\n# `openclaw node`\n\nRun a **headless node host** that connects to the Gateway WebSocket and exposes\n`system.run` / `system.which` on this machine.\n\n## Why use a node host?\n\nUse a node host when you want agents to **run commands on other machines** in your\nnetwork without installing a full macOS companion app there.\n\nCommon use cases:\n\n- Run commands on remote Linux/Windows boxes (build servers, lab machines, NAS).\n- Keep exec **sandboxed** on the gateway, but delegate approved runs to other hosts.\n- Provide a lightweight, headless execution target for automation or CI nodes.\n\nExecution is still guarded by **exec approvals** and per‑agent allowlists on the\nnode host, so you can keep command access scoped and explicit.\n\n## Browser proxy (zero-config)\n\nNode hosts automatically advertise a browser proxy if `browser.enabled` is not\ndisabled on the node. This lets the agent use browser automation on that node\nwithout extra configuration.\n\nDisable it on the node if needed:\n\n```json5\n{\n  nodeHost: {\n    browserProxy: {\n      enabled: false,\n    },\n  },\n}\n```\n\n## Run (foreground)\n\n```bash\nopenclaw node run --host <gateway-host> --port 18789\n```\n\nOptions:\n\n- `--host <host>`: Gateway WebSocket host (default: `127.0.0.1`)\n- `--port <port>`: Gateway WebSocket port (default: `18789`)\n- `--tls`: Use TLS for the gateway connection\n- `--tls-fingerprint <sha256>`: Expected TLS certificate fingerprint (sha256)\n- `--node-id <id>`: Override node id (clears pairing token)\n- `--display-name <name>`: Override the node display name\n\n## Gateway auth for node host\n\n`openclaw node run` and `openclaw node install` resolve gateway auth from config/env (no `--token`/`--password` flags on node commands):\n\n- `OPENCLAW_GATEWAY_TOKEN` / `OPENCLAW_GATEWAY_PASSWORD` are checked first.\n- Then local config fallback: `gateway.auth.token` / `gateway.auth.password`.\n- In local mode, node host intentionally does not inherit `gateway.remote.token` / `gateway.remote.password`.\n- If `gateway.auth.token` / `gateway.auth.password` is explicitly configured via SecretRef and unresolved, node auth resolution fails closed (no remote fallback masking).\n- In `gateway.mode=remote`, remote client fields (`gateway.remote.token` / `gateway.remote.password`) are also eligible per remote precedence rules.\n- Legacy `CLAWDBOT_GATEWAY_*` env vars are ignored for node host auth resolution.\n\n## Service (background)\n\nInstall a headless node host as a user service.\n\n```bash\nopenclaw node install --host <gateway-host> --port 18789\n```\n\nOptions:\n\n- `--host <host>`: Gateway WebSocket host (default: `127.0.0.1`)\n- `--port <port>`: Gateway WebSocket port (default: `18789`)\n- `--tls`: Use TLS for the gateway connection\n- `--tls-fingerprint <sha256>`: Expected TLS certificate fingerprint (sha256)\n- `--node-id <id>`: Override node id (clears pairing token)\n- `--display-name <name>`: Override the node display name\n- `--runtime <runtime>`: Service runtime (`node` or `bun`)\n- `--force`: Reinstall/overwrite if already installed\n\nManage the service:\n\n```bash\nopenclaw node status\nopenclaw node stop\nopenclaw node restart\nopenclaw node uninstall\n```\n\nUse `openclaw node run` for a foreground node host (no service).\n\nService commands accept `--json` for machine-readable output.\n\n## Pairing\n\nThe first connection creates a pending device pairing request (`role: node`) on the Gateway.\nApprove it via:\n\n```bash\nopenclaw devices list\nopenclaw devices approve <requestId>\n```\n\nThe node host stores its node id, token, display name, and gateway connection info in\n`~/.openclaw/node.json`.\n\n## Exec approvals\n\n`system.run` is gated by local exec approvals:\n\n- `~/.openclaw/exec-approvals.json`\n- [Exec approvals](/tools/exec-approvals)\n- `openclaw approvals --node <id|name|ip>` (edit from the Gateway)\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1774151735015}}
{"type":"message","id":"7589fea8","parentId":"becacf3b","timestamp":"2026-03-22T03:55:51.629Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"I see! OpenClaw has a `node` feature where I can install a headless node host on a remote machine, and then I can execute commands on it through the gateway. \n\nThe Paperspace notebook is a Linux machine. If I can install the OpenClaw node on it, then I could execute commands through it. But the challenge is getting the node installed on Paperspace in the first place.\n\nActually wait - the Paperspace notebook already has a gateway running. And I'm already communicating with it through Telegram. The issue is that the Paperspace machine's exec tool is available to the OpenClaw running ON that machine, not to me directly.\n\nHmm, but if I'm the main agent running on the gateway (which is on the local Windows machine), I don't have exec access to Paperspace unless there's a node configured there.\n \nSo the real problem is that the Paperspace notebook isn't set up as an OpenClaw node, which means there's no way for me to execute commands on it directly. The gateway on my Windows PC can't reach into Paperspace to run anything.\n\nI could try setting up SSH access to Paperspace, but that would require obtaining the actual IP address and SSH credentials from the Paperspace API rather than just the hostname. Let me query the Paperspace API to get the machine's public IP and connection details so I can establish an SSH tunnel.\n\nActually, I should check if the gradient CLI that's installed in Python 3.12 might have the ability to connect to Paperspace notebooks directly, rather than trying to hack around with SSH.","thinkingSignature":"ab3a77008fb9de6e8e13334b903a1ccee6a4ba52845e774c2324aa49dd247238"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_i53s1a3rezup_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"C:\\Users\\Zwmar\\AppData\\Local\\Programs\\Python\\Python312\\python.exe -c \"\nfrom gradient import Gradient\ng = G